{"id":"1503.07733","submitter":"Lara Benfatto","authors":"T. Cea, C. Castellani, G. Seibold and L. Benfatto","title":"Non-relativistic dynamics of the amplitude (Higgs) mode in\n  superconductors","comments":"Final version, expanded discussion on the optics. Supplemental\n  Material included","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 115, 157002 (2015)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.115.157002","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Despite the formal analogy with the Higgs particle, the amplitude\nfluctuations of the order parameter in weakly-coupled superconductors do not\nidentify a real mode with a Lorentz-invariant dynamics. Indeed, its resonance\noccurs at $2\\Delta_0$, which coincides with the threshold $2E_{gap}$ for\nquasiparticle excitations, that spoil any relativistic dynamics. Here we\ninvestigate the fate of the Higgs mode in the unconventional case where\n$2E_{gap}$ becomes larger than $2\\Delta_0$, as due to strong coupling or strong\ndisorder. We show that also in this situation the amplitude fluctuations never\nidentify a real mode at $2\\Delta_0$, since such \"bosonic\" limit is always\nreached via a strong mixing with the phase fluctuations, which dominate the\nlow-energy part of the spectrum. Our results have direct implications for the\ninterpretation of the sub-gap optical absorption in disordered superconductors.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 26 Mar 2015 13:42:52 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 9 Apr 2015 08:43:18 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 2 Nov 2015 09:51:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-11-03"}
